@Michael Weiland

The US should get rid of $1 and $5 notes too.

Smallest note here is ¬•1000 ($10 in usage, not so much in value anymore). ¬•500 ($5) and smaller are coins. At first it took some getting used to, but now I find it a much better system (although I barely ever use cash nowadays).

@Elizabeth Connors
Because it costs a lot of money to replace dollar bills when they wear out, which is very fast compared to coins. 

We've made halfhearted attempts to get people to use dollar coins, but experience in other countries has shown that the only reliable way to get people to use the unit coin is to eliminate the unit note.

@Michael Weiland

The US's attempt at a dollar coin was a failure, I think because there was no attempt to get the public involved during development of the design. Unlike the Canadian quarter and loonie, the US quarter and dollar are impossible to distinguish by feel. Plus Jimmy Carter couldn't catch a break no matter what he did. 

A friend once told me that when he was a kid his mother gave him a dollar every day to get lunch for himself and his little brother. He was able to get a slice and soda for each of them and get change back. Clearly it's time to get rid of the dollar bill.

